[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4079[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4080[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4081[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4082[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Gap Between This and Production
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4083[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4084[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This demo runs end-to-end and produces the right structure (consent records with state-specific provisions and per-data-source consent matrices, caregiver records with proxy-access scope, longitudinal-coordination-state records with provenance references, provenance-journal entries on a separately-keyed path, referral-lifecycle records moving through the state machine, transition-of-care records with protocol-defined steps, seam-flag records with named clinical-leadership ownership, coordination-decision records with full audit trail, weekly digests gated by consent), but the distance between it and a real care-coordination assistant serving an institution's chronic-care population is significant. Here is where that distance lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4085[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4086[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real cross-organizational ingestion layer.** The demo's per-source adapters are illustrative dictionaries; production has each adapter as a separate Lambda or service with authentication (per-organization auth flow, OAuth where supported, mTLS otherwise), rate-limit handling (per-organization rate limits, backoff strategies), error-handling and retries with idempotency, format translation (HL7 v2 to FHIR, NCPDP to FHIR, vendor-specific to FHIR), sensitive-record classification with per-category routing, and provenance-recording on a separately-keyed KMS path. The HL7 listener handles ADT and ORU message types with vocabulary-specific parsing; the FHIR poller handles FHIR R4 with USCDI v3 conformance and Bulk Data Access for population workflows; the claims-feed processor handles 837/835 transactions or vendor-specific equivalents; the pharmacy adapters handle NCPDP SCRIPT or vendor APIs; the home-health adapters handle vendor-specific APIs; the HIE/TEFCA adapter handles QHIN-mediated cross-organizational queries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4087[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4088[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Bedrock Agents action groups (or a custom LLM-and-tool orchestrator).** The demo runs canned responses from `MockBedrockRuntime`. Production wires the coordination tools (`coordination_state_retrieve`, `referral_lifecycle_retrieve`, `encounter_retrieve`, `medication_list_reconcile`, `open_followups_retrieve`, `seam_flags_retrieve`, `protocol_retrieve`, `patient_education_content_retrieve`, `care_team_alert_propose`, `patient_action_propose`, `follow_up_schedule`, `escalation_propose`, `provenance_retrieve`) as Bedrock Agents action groups (one OpenAPI spec per tool with the argument schema, the response schema, and the docstring the LLM uses to decide when to call it), gives the agent the institutional persona prompt with explicit non-clinician scoping and speaker-role-aware behavior, the longitudinal-coordination-context payload, and the Knowledge Base bindings (coordination protocols, patient education, conversation history), and lets the LLM drive the multi-step reasoning, the tool-call orchestration, and the citation-grounded language while the citation-grounding verifier and the scope-filter keep the structure honest.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4089[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4090[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Bedrock Knowledge Base ingestion of the coordination-protocol corpus, the patient-education library, and the longitudinal conversation history.** The demo's `TRANSITION_PROTOCOLS` is two illustrative items. Production has three Knowledge Bases: one ingesting the institution's curated coordination-protocol corpus (transition-of-care protocols by destination setting, referral-tracking protocols by specialty and urgency, post-discharge protocols by admission type, post-procedure protocols by procedure category, medication-reconciliation protocols, condition-specific coordination playbooks for high-prevalence multi-condition combinations), with metadata filters for destination setting, admission type, specialty, urgency tier, audience, language, reading level, and version; one ingesting the patient-education library with multilingual and multi-reading-level variants; and one indexing the patient-specific conversation history. Each corpus has named ownership at the relevant clinical-specialty leadership team plus the care-management leadership plus compliance, with documented review cadence (annual, plus on each material update) and versioned change-management workflow. Stale retrieval is a serious failure mode the corpus governance prevents.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4091[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4092[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Bedrock Guardrails configuration.** The demo passes `GUARDRAIL_ID` but does not configure a Guardrail. Production configures restricted-topic filters for diagnosis-attempted, prescription-attempted, dose-titration-attempted, treatment-recommendation-beyond-existing-orders, therapy-attempted (route to recipe 11.8), triage-attempted (route to recipe 11.6), benefits-quote-attempted (route to recipe 11.5), and other adjacent-recipe scope-violations, plus contextual-grounding for the response-generation steps. The Guardrail is pinned to a specific version, tested against a held-out evaluation set including coordination-specific injection cases (manipulate seam-flag routing, manipulate scope discipline to elicit clinical recommendations, manipulate proxy-scope to reach restricted records), and updated on a versioned-rollout cadence with canary traffic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4093[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4094[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real AWS HealthLake datastore for FHIR-native chart context.** The demo's `MockHealthLake` is an in-memory dict. Production wires HealthLake to ingest from multiple FHIR sources (the institution's primary EHR, partner organizations' FHIR APIs, HIE/TEFCA query results), with per-resource-type indexing (Patient, Encounter, Condition, MedicationRequest, MedicationStatement, Observation, DiagnosticReport, ServiceRequest, CarePlan, AllergyIntolerance, Immunization, Coverage), and queries run from the tool Lambdas with appropriate IAM scoping. Where the institution's primary EHR exposes FHIR directly, the assistant queries it directly; where multiple sources contribute, HealthLake serves as the normalization layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4095[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4096[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Step Functions transition-of-care workflows with version-controlled state machines.** The demo's `MockStepFunctions` accumulates execution metadata. Production has each transition workflow defined in Amazon States Language with states for the protocol-defined steps (welcome-home check-in with timeout-based escalation, medication reconciliation, follow-up appointment validation, home-health or DME order validation, patient education, red-flag warning instructions, symptom-monitoring engagement, closure verification), version-controlled in Git, signed off by clinical leadership, and updated through the institutional change-management workflow. State-machine outputs feed the audit pipeline; failed executions feed the operations queue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4097[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4098[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real referral-lifecycle state machine with deterministic transition logic.** The demo's lifecycle is a small dictionary. Production has the state machine encoded as a deterministic worker with full audit logging, time-window enforcement per protocol, and integration with the institution's scheduling systems for state changes triggered by external events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4099[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real seam-detection rule library with named clinical-leadership ownership per rule.** The demo's `SEAM_DETECTION_RULES` is six illustrative rules. Production has 50-200 rules with named ownership (patient safety officer, pharmacy director, care-management director, post-discharge care coordinator director, ambulatory quality director, etc.), effective dates, version histories, sampled review for precision and recall against a held-out evaluation set, and clinical-leadership signoff before deployment. Rules update through a versioned-rollout cadence with canary traffic and rollback discipline. Multi-quarter clinical-content development work to mature.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real medication-reconciliation rules with pharmacy-informatics partnership.** The demo's reconciliation is a thin dose-matching heuristic. Production has medication-naming canonicalization (RxNorm with full vocabulary lookup), dose representation (UCUM with full unit conversion), dosing-instruction parsing (best-effort sig parser with confidence scores; fall-back to preserved free-text), and discrepancy-detection rules owned by pharmacy informatics and signed off by pharmacy leadership. Multi-quarter work to mature.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real cross-organizational consent posture with regulatory-counsel review.** The demo records `state_of_residence` and `sources_consented`. Production has the per-state and per-sensitive-category consent matrix encoded in policy and operationalized in the consent-language, the data-handling, the retention, the patient-access, and the patient-deletion workflows. State-specific provisions for California's CMIA and LPS Act, New York's MHL, Illinois's MHDDC, Massachusetts's Chapter 123, plus 42 CFR Part 2 for substance-use treatment data, plus the Information Blocking Rule's required-data-sharing provisions, plus state-specific HIV-record and genetic-test-result protections, plus state-specific adolescent confidentiality. Legal counsel familiar with this landscape reviews the consent posture before launch and on each material change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real caregiver-as-first-class-participant identity model with state-law compliance.** The demo's caregiver record is a thin dict. Production has caregiver designation with state-specific consent forms (notarized HCP/POA documentation where required), proxy-access scope per state law (some states have specific rules for adolescents and aging adults), sensitive-record carve-outs honored at every tool call, separate authentication credentials for the caregiver app, separate session management, and operationally enforced access scoping at every coordination-state retrieval. Legal counsel reviews state-specific variations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real DynamoDB and S3 wiring with separate KMS keys for sensitive surfaces.** The mocks are dictionaries; production is DynamoDB tables with on-demand or provisioned capacity, customer-managed KMS keys, point-in-time recovery on the patient-coordination, coordination-state, referral-lifecycle, transition-of-care, seam-flag, caregiver, conversation, ledger, decision-record, provenance-journal, and consent-record tables, TTL on the conversation-state table tuned for typical session durations, and DynamoDB Streams emitting change events for downstream consumers. The coordination-decision-record-journal S3 bucket has SSE-KMS, Object Lock in compliance mode, lifecycle to S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval after 30 days and Glacier Deep Archive after 90, and retention sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, the state's medical-record retention rules (often 7-10+ years for adult records, sometimes longer for pediatric), 42 CFR Part 2 retention where applicable, FDA SaMD post-market obligations where applicable, and the institutional regulatory floor. The provenance-journal archive uses a **separately-managed customer-managed KMS key** with separate access-control surfaces; a leaked credential to the general workload should not give an attacker the provenance chain. The coordination-decision-record archive likewise uses a **separately-managed customer-managed KMS key** for the same reason.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **KMS customer-managed keys per data class with separate keys for the provenance and decision-record surfaces.** Every PHI-bearing resource uses customer-managed KMS keys with key rotation enabled. Different KMS keys for different data classes (general coordination data, **provenance journal on a separately-managed key**, **coordination-decision-record on a separately-managed key**, audit archive, Secrets Manager secrets) limit the blast radius of any single key compromise. Key access is scoped to the specific principals that need it; CloudTrail logs every key-usage event.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **VPC and VPC endpoints.** The chat-handler Lambda runs internet-facing through API Gateway. The ingestion Lambdas (HL7 listener, FHIR poller, claims processor, pharmacy consumer, home-health consumer, HIE adapter) and the tool Lambdas that call EHRs, care-team workflow systems, mandatory-reporting pathways, and care-navigation systems run in a VPC with PrivateLink (where supported) or a tightly-scoped NAT-gateway path with allow-list. VPC endpoints for Bedrock, DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, EventBridge, Step Functions, MWAA, HealthLake, Connect, Pinpoint, Comprehend Medical, SageMaker (where used), and CloudWatch Logs keep AWS-internal traffic off the public internet.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **WAF tuning for coordination traffic patterns.** Coordination endpoints have rate limits tuned for chat-typical traffic plus the ingestion-volume profile. Acute-symptom presentations are routed through a separate priority lane that the standard rate limit does not gate. Bot-detection rules allow legitimate accessibility tools while blocking automated abuse.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-Lambda IAM least privilege with separation of concerns and provenance-journal isolation.** The demo uses a single set of mocked credentials. Production has one IAM role per Lambda (chat handler, input screening, identity handling, each ingestion adapter, each tool implementation, seam-detection rule engine, transition-of-care worker, referral-lifecycle worker, medication-reconciliation worker, output screening, coordination-decision-record persistence, provenance-journal-recording on the separately-managed KMS path, care-team-reporting, audit archival, outcome correlation), each scoped to the specific resource ARNs the Lambda touches. The provenance-journal-recording Lambda is the only path with write access to the provenance journal and the only path with `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the `PROVENANCE_KMS_KEY_ID`. The chat-handler Lambda has Bedrock invocation and read-write on the conversation tables, but no direct access to the EHRs or the provenance journal. None of the assistant's Lambdas have write access to the clinical record except for institutionally-approved coordination-event records (FHIR Communication for the conversation log; FHIR ServiceRequest for follow-up scheduling where the institution permits assistant-originated requests; with explicit patient consent and clinical-leadership signoff).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy artifact with regulatory-counsel review.** The institutional regulatory positioning (informational coordination support with clinician oversight, or registered SaMD if the assistant produces clinical recommendations beyond what existing clinicians have ordered) is documented, reviewed by FDA-experienced regulatory counsel, and maintained as the deployment evolves. Architectural changes that may affect regulatory positioning are reviewed against the artifact. Post-market surveillance obligations for SaMD-positioned deployments are operationalized. The institutional malpractice insurer is part of the policy review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort accuracy and equity monitoring with launch gates.** The demo emits CloudWatch metrics with a few dimensions, which is enough for per-program dashboards. Production stratifies by cohort axes the institution monitors (per-language, per-channel, per-condition, per-age-cohort, per-sex, per-social-determinant-flag, per-caregiver-presence, per-integration-coverage), plus two-axis cohorts, and treats per-cohort threshold compliance as a launch gate. Engagement rate, attrition rate, referral closure rate, transition-of-care completion rate, medication-reconciliation accuracy, seam-detection precision and recall, faithfulness rate, citation-coverage rate, escalation rate, and outcome metrics (avoidable-readmission rate, avoidable-ED-utilization rate) all get sliced. A cohort with materially lower coverage or higher seam-detection-miss rate after controlling for condition mix is a clinical-quality and equity issue that aggregate metrics hide. Launch is gated on every cohort meeting the threshold, not on the institution-wide average.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline with operational ownership and multi-year time horizon.** The demo's outcome-correlation is a stub. Production has the pipeline pulling subsequent encounter records (readmissions, ED visits, primary-care encounters), claims-data utilization (avoided procedures, duplicate services), referral-closure trajectories, transition-of-care completion trajectories, medication-reconciliation accuracy trajectories, and (with appropriate caution about attribution) total-cost-of-care correlation against propensity-matched comparison cohorts. Multi-window correlation (30-day, 90-day, 6-month, 12-month, 24-month, 36-month) against utilization, clinical, and patient-experience outcomes. Operational ownership is jointly held by clinical leadership, care management, the data science team, operations, compliance, and (where applicable) the participating payer's analytics and quality teams. The pipeline is multi-quarter to multi-year post-launch work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multilingual deployment with validated translations.** The demo is English-only. Most U.S. payer and Medicare Advantage populations include meaningful non-English-speaking groups. Per-language work: validated coordination-protocol translations (with clinical equivalency review by clinicians, not just linguistic translation), validated patient-education translations, validated regulatory-disclaimer phrasings, per-language tone and persona calibration, per-language equity monitoring. Spanish-language deployment typically takes three to four additional months beyond the English go-live; ad-hoc machine translation is not acceptable for protocol-grounded coordination instruction or patient-education delivery.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Voice-channel deployment for accessibility.** The conversational logic above runs in chat. Adding a voice channel through Amazon Connect with Lex V2 reuses the orchestration logic but adds ASR and TTS layers, tighter latency budgets, voice-specific design (slower pacing, brief responses, accessibility considerations), and ASR error monitoring scoped to the coordination vocabulary. Crisis-pathway integrity is preserved across channels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Citation-grounding verifier with structured-output schema validation.** The demo's `_verify_faithfulness` implements a heuristic check. Production runs an independent verifier model with structured-output schema validation between Bedrock generation and response delivery, grounding every coordination-state assertion to a cited provenance entry, every protocol instruction to a cited protocol with version stamping, and every patient-education delivery to a cited library entry. The faithfulness check uses rule-based contradiction detection, omission detection, a regenerate-attempt budget, and a fall-back-to-safe-response default. Per-cohort faithfulness-failure rate is a launch-gate metric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR Bulk Data Access pipeline for population workflows.** The demo runs per-event ingestion. Production augments per-event ingestion with population-scale Bulk Data Access (Flat FHIR) to support program-wide analytics and seam-detection. MWAA orchestrates the bulk-data jobs; the seam-detection rule engine runs both per-event and on bulk batches.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Comprehend Medical entity extraction over patient-and-caregiver-reported text.** The demo doesn't use Comprehend Medical. Production runs Comprehend Medical's `DetectEntitiesV2` over patient-and-caregiver-reported free-text to extract structured medical entities (medications, dosages, conditions, procedures) for matching against the coordination state, with confidence-scored output and human review for low-confidence matches.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **SageMaker custom seam-detection classifiers for harder cases.** Several seam-detection patterns (subtle decompensation signals, complex medication-discrepancy reasoning, caregiver-burden trajectory) benefit from custom-trained classifiers; SageMaker provides the hosted-inference endpoint where deployed. The deterministic rules form the floor; the classifiers handle the harder cases with calibrated confidence and human-review fall-back.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Connect contact-center integration for warm-handoff to human care managers.** The demo's `MockClinicianQueue` accumulates handoffs in memory. Production wires `connect_client.start_chat_contact` to route to the licensed-care-manager queue with the conversation context attached. The care-management workforce (employed or contracted) is sized to the patient population and the expected handoff volume, with peak-hour capacity, per-state coverage where state-specific licensure is required, and per-language coverage where multiple languages are deployed. Under-sized capacity is a safety gap; the warm-handoff infrastructure is a primary safety architecture, not a fallback. The dominant operational cost is the human care-management workforce, not the AWS infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation operations for inappropriate responses or missed seams.** When a patient or clinician disputes a bot response, when a seam is missed, or when a faithfulness drift is reported, the operations team reproduces the conversation, retrieves cited content, and either confirms the bot followed protocol or identifies the deviation and feeds the failure mode into the improvement loop. Tooling for this workflow is part of production scope and is reviewed by compliance. Disputes are retained for the longer of the institutional record-retention floor and any FDA SaMD post-market obligations. A missed high-acuity seam triggers an immediate clinical-leadership review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery and degraded-mode operation with crisis-pathway integrity preservation.** When upstream dependencies fail (Bedrock outage, HealthLake unreachable, EHR APIs unreachable, protocol corpus unavailable, Connect contact-center unreachable), the bot must degrade gracefully. The minimum behavior is "I'm having trouble pulling that data right now; for anything urgent please contact your care team or call 911" with direct routing to crisis resources. Crisis-pathway integrity is preserved across all degraded states; this is a non-negotiable engineering constraint. Per-source failover behavior is documented and tested quarterly. Cross-region failover for Bedrock, the institutional integrations, and the warm-handoff workforce queue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-rights workflow for conversation logs, decision records, and provenance journal.** Conversation logs are dense longitudinal PHI plus may include cross-organizational data with sharing implications. Decision records are clinically significant. The provenance journal is separately governed. Patients have rights to access all of these (with state-specific variations on what they can access in real time vs. after clinical review). The institution has retention obligations that vary by state and by record class. Build the workflow: how a patient requests their conversation history, decision records, and provenance entries; how the requests are authenticated; how the data is produced; how deletion requests interact with retention obligations; how the records are referenced from the patient portal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous-improvement loop with structured failure-mode labeling.** Production transcripts surface presenting situations the team did not have content for, retrieval gaps in the protocol corpus, seam-detection misses, citation gaps, scope violations, and patterns in the coordination-decision-record journal that point to operational issues. Build the labeling and review workflow: review production transcripts weekly with clinical leadership, the care-management workforce, compliance, and data science, propose protocol updates, propose seam-rule updates, propose prompt-tuning updates, run them through the evaluation set, deploy via versioned aliases, monitor for regressions. The bot's quality at month six is determined by whether someone is doing this work, not by how good the launch was.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy rigor.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination platforms with FHIR integration, claims-feed processing, transition-of-care workflows, and (in some cases) hybrid-coordination workforces. Most major institutions in production run a hybrid: in-house orchestration layer for the institution's preferred infrastructure and consent posture, vendor partnership for the cross-organizational integration substrate (HIE participation, TEFCA QHIN access, claims-feed plumbing), and integration with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Testing.** There are no tests in this demo. A production pipeline has unit tests for the input-screening logic, the continuous-emergency-screening logic (each acuity category fires correctly across condition contexts; hypotheticals and past-tense framing do not false-positive; emergency-language variants by language and demographic cohort are covered), the sensitive-disclosure detection (each category routes correctly; mandatory-reporting flag is set correctly per state), the consent-gating logic (every consent-gated path checks the current consent posture, not a stale snapshot), the per-source ingestion adapters (each source type parses, validates, normalizes, and emits triggers correctly), the provenance-journal-recording (every ingested data point produces a provenance entry with integrity hash), the seam-detection rule engine (each rule fires correctly on its target patterns; precision and recall are calibrated against held-out cases), the referral-lifecycle state machine (every state transition is validated; invalid transitions are rejected; aging rules trigger correctly), the transition-of-care workflows (each protocol's steps fire in the correct order; completion criteria are validated), the medication-reconciliation logic (RxNorm canonicalization, dose comparison, cross-pharmacy discrepancy detection, cross-clinician conflict detection for high-risk classes), the citation-grounding verifier (every coordination-state assertion traces to a citation; citations include version stamps), the proxy-scope enforcement (caregiver tool calls are filtered by scope), the output-screening replacement logic, and the longitudinal-coordination-state update logic. Integration tests against a Bedrock test environment, non-production EHR endpoints with synthetic data, a non-production HealthLake datastore, a non-production protocol corpus, and a non-production Connect contact-center. End-to-end tests that simulate full coordination journeys through representative scenarios. Never use real PHI in test fixtures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Observability beyond metrics.** The demo emits CloudWatch metrics but no traces and no structured logs ready for cross-call investigation. Production runs CloudWatch Logs Insights queries that join across the API Gateway logs, the chat-handler logs, the ingestion-adapter logs, the seam-detection logs, the Bedrock invocation traces, the tool-Lambda logs, the coordination-decision-record journal, the provenance journal (with restricted access), and the audit records by session_id and patient_id. AWS X-Ray traces show the latency contribution of each step. When a single conversation goes wrong, the on-call engineer needs to reconstruct the full trace in seconds, not minutes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cost monitoring and per-conversation attribution.** Bedrock's per-token charges, Knowledge Bases' per-query charges, the vector store's hosting charges, HealthLake's per-resource and per-query charges, Pinpoint's per-message charges, Connect's per-handoff charges, Comprehend Medical's per-character charges, and the per-call costs of the upstream-system integrations add up. Some coordination conversations are dramatically more expensive than others (a multi-turn post-discharge welcome-home conversation with extensive medication-reconciliation, transition-orchestration follow-through, and care-team alert generation costs more than a one-shot referral status check). The per-program and per-active-member analytics let the operations team see which segments are economically efficient and which warrant tooling improvements. Per-active-member infrastructure cost is small relative to the cost of a single avoided readmission, but per-conversation attribution makes the cost story explicit. The dominant operational cost is the licensed-care-management workforce, not the AWS infrastructure; under-investing in the workforce is a safety gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    4155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
